abel, so I should verify the selector matches the pod labels. I'm wondering if KARMA re-injects the adversary when entering stage_06, or if the lifecycle is strictly tied to the inject_at_stage and lift_at_stage markers. The adversary config shows inject at stage_05 and lift at stage_07, so the adversary should persist through stage_06—but I'm puzzled why the lift record appears in the stage_05 adversary.json when the lift shouldn't happen until stage_07. Let me focus on checking the current state of the es-http service selector instead of getting lost in the KARMA internals.\n\nNow I'm looking at the service mapping and cluster state: the es-http service targets pods with label `app: es-cluster`, which matches es-cluster-0, es-cluster-1, and es-cluster-2. The cluster health is GREEN with 5 nodes all present according to _cat/nodes. But the oracle says \"A node failed to rejoin\"—yet all 5 nodes appear to be in the cluster right now. I need to check whether these pods are actually joined to the cluster or just running as containers.\n\nWait, I'm realizing the configured adversary is \"http-service-selector-drift\", not the seed-hosts scenario. But the stage case is \"seed-hosts-repair\", which means the apply phase should have scaled down to 2 replicas, deleted the PVC for es-cluster-2, scaled back up to 3, and corrupted the ConfigMap with wrong seed_hosts. However, the apply was skipped because the probe passed. So the current state must be inherited from earlier stages—I need to trace back what happened in the previous \"seed-hosts-repair\" run.\n\nLet me check the oracle and evidence files from stage_03 to see if it passed and what state it left the cluster in.","signature":""}],"stop_reason":null,"stop_sequence":null,"stop_details":null,"usage":{"input_tokens":1,"cache_creation_input_tokens":4911,"cache_read_input_tokens":48351,"cache_creation":{"ephemeral_5m_input_tokens":0,"ephemeral_1h_input_tokens":4911},"output_tokens":19,"service_tier":"standard","inferenc