ee nodes, the ConfigMap has the right seed hosts, and the app-data index is readable. But the prompt mentions a node failing to rejoin after restart, yet everything appears healthy and green. I'm wondering if the \"http-service-selector-drift\" adversary is still active and I'm not catching it, or if I need to reconsider when this adversary is actually supposed to be running—it should be active during stage_06, not stage_05. in the same namespace, short names should resolve fine. So that's probably not the issue. Let me think about what seed_hosts repair actually means—maybe the ConfigMap got corrupted or the seed hosts list is incomplete or pointing to nodes that don't exist anymore. The http-service-selector-drift adversary modifies the es-http service selector, which is a different fault mechanism than a node failing to rejoin. I'm wondering if there's actually a separate fault configured through the es-config-seed-hosts-drift adversary, but that doesn't appear to be set up in the config. Let me reconsider the actual state—the _cat/nodes output showed 5 nodes, but when I count the running pods across all clusters (es-cluster with 3 pods, es-alpha with 3 pods, es-beta with 1 pod, and es-data-new with 2 pods), I need to figure out which nodes are actually part of the es-cluster and whether one has genuinely failed to rejoin.\n\nLooking at the pod ages more carefully, es-cluster-0 is only 2 minutes old while the others are 4-5 minutes old, suggesting a recent restart that might not have fully completed the cluster join process. I'm also realizing the precondition's first probe was checking something specific with kubectl in the elasticsearch namespace that I should revisit.","signature":""}],"stop_reason":null,"stop_sequence":null,"stop_details":null,"usage":{"input_tokens":1,"cache_creation_input_tokens":1013,"cache_read_input_tokens":58995,"cache_creation":{"ephemeral_5m_input_tokens":0,"ephemeral_1h_input_tokens":1013},"output_tokens":37,"service_tier":"standard"