t the expected node count, then validates the cluster health against that number.\n\nBut here's the thing—the stage says there's a fault, yet the precondition probe passed, meaning the system found the cluster in a functional state. If the probe passed, the apply step gets skipped entirely, which means no fault would have been injected in the first place.\n\nLet me trace through this more carefully. The adversary fault from stage_05 (the http-service-selector-drift) should still be active during stage_06. I'm checking the current es-http service selector now—it shows `app: es-cluster`, but the adversary should have changed it to `app: es-cluster-wrong`. That's not matching up. Either the adversary was reapplied at stage_06 start instead of stage_05, or I'm misunderstanding the deployment timeline. Looking at the config, the adversary is injected at the beginning of stage_05 and lifted at stage_07, so it should definitely be active now.\n\nI think what's happening is that during stage_05 (the scale-up-new-nodeset operation), the agent likely patched the service selector back to `app: es-cluster`, undoing the adversary's change. Then when the lift probe ran at the end of stage_05, it found the selector was already fixed, so the lift was skipped. Now I'm wondering whether KARMA re-injects the adversary for stages between injection and lift, or if it expects the adversary to persist on its own.\n\nLet me step back and look at what the actual cluster state is right now. The problem statement says a node failed to rejoin after restart, and the hint points to the es-http service selector being wrong. Maybe the selector really is pointing to the wrong label, and even though the cluster appears green, the oracle queries fail because they route through es-http. I should test this directly from the curl-test pod to see what's actually happening.","signature":""}],"stop_reason":null,"stop_sequence":null,"stop_details":null,"usage":{"input_tokens":1,"cache_creation_input_tokens"