{"type":"assistant","message":{"model":"claude-sonnet-4-6","id":"msg_01NAD2GDDZaM47hQnrLaHn5u","type":"message","role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"thinking","thinking":"Now I understand the adversary lifecycle. The `lift` in `adversary.json` is recorded when the lift actually runs. Looking at the adversary.json in stage_05:\n\n```json\n\"lift\": {\n    \"ok\": true,\n    \"lifted_ids\": [],\n    \"output\": \"\"\n}\n```\n\nThis means the lift was RUN (during stage_05 cleanup) with the lift probe FAILING (since `lifted_ids` is empty and `ok: true` with no output). The lift probe checks:\n```\n/bin/sh -c \"kubectl -n elasticsearch get service es-http -o jsonpath='{.spec.selector.app}' | grep -q 'es-cluster-wrong'\"\n```\n\nThe probe is looking for `es-cluster-wrong` in the selector. If the selector is actually `es-cluster` (not `es-cluster-wrong`), the probe fails. With `on_probe_fail: skip` as the default, a failed probe means the condition is already resolved, so it returns success with no lifted IDs.\n\nThis explains why `lifted_ids: []` and `ok: true` — the lift probe failed because the adversary wasn't found, meaning it was either already fixed by the agent in the previous stage or never actually applied despite the deploy output showing the service was patched. Maybe the `lift_at_stage: stage_07` is actually a deadline rather than a strict timing constraint, and the adversary gets lifted whenever it's detected as fixed or at the end of the inject stage, whichever comes first. The adversary.json records when the lift actually happened in stage_05, even though the config specified stage_07 as the target.\n\nLet me trace through how KARMA actually manages the adversary lifecycle in its workflow runtime to understand the exact mechanics.","signature":""}],"stop_reason":null,"stop_sequence":null,"stop_details":null,"usage":{"input_tokens":1,"cache_creation_input_tokens":4363,"cache_read_input_tokens":66807,"cache_creation":{"ephemeral_5m_input_tokens":0,"ephemera