{"type":"assistant","message":{"model":"claude-sonnet-4-6","id":"msg_01HNxc4ZwMNhzhg9wpta6JTL","type":"message","role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"thinking","thinking":"Now I can see the HISTORY of what happened. Looking at the es-cluster-2 logs:\n\n1. At 07:04:30 - es-cluster-2 was elected as master with 2 nodes joined (es-cluster-1 and es-cluster-2)\n2. At 07:04:34 - the OLD es-cluster-0 (IP 10.244.0.186) was REMOVED from the cluster\n3. At 07:05:17 - the NEW es-cluster-0 (IP 10.244.0.215) was ADDED back to the cluster\n\nSo there definitely was a fault—es-cluster-0 restarted and got a new IP, leaving it disconnected from the cluster for about 43 seconds before rejoining. The cluster is healthy now with all 5 nodes, but the precondition check likely ran right around 07:04:30 when the pod was still missing.\n\nThe issue was that es-cluster-0 restarted and temporarily failed to rejoin, while the precondition passed because es-cluster-1 and es-cluster-2 were still running. Looking at the timeline more carefully, a new election started at 07:04:30 with just those 2 nodes, the old es-cluster-0 was removed at 07:04:34, and then the new one rejoined at 07:05:17. I need to figure out whether this was an intentional fault I'm supposed to fix or just a transient issue that resolved itself. all 5 nodes are present and the cluster is currently healthy.","signature":""}],"stop_reason":null,"stop_sequence":null,"stop_details":null,"usage":{"input_tokens":1,"cache_creation_input_tokens":5783,"cache_read_input_tokens":74197,"cache_creation":{"ephemeral_5m_input_tokens":0,"ephemeral_1h_input_tokens":5783},"output_tokens":22,"service_tier":"standard","inference_geo":"not_available"},"diagnostics":null,"context_management":null},"parent_tool_use_id":null,"session_id":"df254869-6326-4314-8a88-6d3c82cf9641","uuid":"6e4f5f67-eca6-4896-aad6-b80aef0a3d61","request_id":"req_011CcMfs8R6MTdCR7FGkoDrH"}
